{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516029"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:37:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:37:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12547"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12547"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.03,0.05,0.01,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5046"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77729"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5046"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12547"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63245"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42779"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77729"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old male patient presents to his general practice with thick, discoloured, and brittle toenails. He is uncertain about the duration of these symptoms. There is no pain, tenderness, or fever. He has a past medical history of diabetes mellitus and takes metformin. On examination, there is yellowish discolouration and thickening of the toenails, with the separation of the nail plate from the nail bed. There is no obvious haematoma, nail pitting, atrophy, ridging, or surrounding bruising. The fingernails have no abnormalities. A sample of nail clippings is sent for microscopy and culture.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Onychogryphosis","Psoriasis","Lichen planus","Nail trauma","Onychomycosis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe scenario is consistent with a diagnosis of Tinea unguium, also known as \u003Cstrong\u003Eonychomycosis\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s history of diabetes mellitus may increase his risk of developing fungal infections. Onychomycosis can also commonly occur with co-existing tinea pedis which can appear as unilateral itchy, scaly erosions between the toes. The initial treatment for onychomycosis depends on the severity of the infection and the patient\u0027s medical history. The appropriate initial treatment would be oral terbinafine. Topical antifungals such as ciclopirox and terbinafine may be used weekly as prophylaxis following successful treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic autoimmune disease that affects the skin and nails. Signs may include thick, discoloured, and pitted nails including ridging and onycholysis. Skin manifestations include red, scaly patches/plaques of skin on the body, commonly found on the scalp, elbows, and knees.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELichen planus\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory condition that can affect the skin, nails, and mucous membranes. Signs may include flat-topped, itchy, purple bumps on the skin with common sites including the wrists, lower back, and ankles. Plaques resolve after a few months leaving greyish-brown post-inflammatory macules that can take up to a year to fade. Nail changes such as nail thinning, splitting, onychorrhexis, and ridging can occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENail trauma \u003C/strong\u003Ecan result in the separation of the nail from the nailbed which can be mistaken for onychomycosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnychogryphosis is \u003C/strong\u003Ea disorder of nail plate growth that is characterized by yellow-brown thickening of the nail with associated hyperkeratosis, elongation, and increased curvature. It is often described as a \u0027ram\u0027s horn nail\u0027.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Onychomycosis results in thickened, discoloured, and brittle nails, with or without separation from the nail bed.","Diabetes mellitus increases the risk of fungal infections, including onychomycosis."],"references":["Fletcher CL, Hay RJ, Smeeton NC. Onychomycosis: The development of a clinical diagnostic aid for toenail disease. Part I. Establishing discriminating historical and clinical features. Br J Dermatol 2004;150(4):701\u201305. doi: 10.1111/j.0007-0963.2004.05871.x. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15099366/","Kreijkamp-Kaspers S, Hawke K, Guo L, et al. Oral antifungal medication for toenail onychomycosis. Cochrane Database Syst Rev 2017;7:CD010031. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD010031.pub2. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28707751/","Gupta AK, Ryder JE, Johnson AM. Cumulative meta-analysis of systemic antifungal agents for the treatment of onychomycosis. Br J Dermatol 2004;150(3):537\u201344. doi: 10.1046/j.1365-2133.2003.05728.x. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15030339/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63245"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12547"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63245","links":{"sel